<br>
People don't hate out freedoms, they hate our policies, and the culture we export (because our culture tends to open up and &quot;modernize&quot; conservative, reactionary societies).  Blaming their hatred on jealousy over our economic success, democratic process, etc... is a cop out.  <br>
<br>
I think the exporting of US culture has done some wonderful things in the world.  But I also think our foriegn policy continues to do more harm than good to the long term-interests of peace and prosperity for our nation.<br>
<br>
We are about to invade Iraq based on dubious evidence that they may still have an effective program to develop nuclear, chemical, and biological weapons.  I say dubious because the CIA has said that they do not see Iraq as a serious or immediate threat.  Read:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://story.news.yahoo.com/news?tmpl=story&u=/ap/20021009/ap_on_go_pr_wh/us_iraq_132">story.news.yahoo.com/news...s_iraq_132</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Now North Korea just admitted openly that they have a very advanced nuclear program, and &quot;even more powerful&quot; weapons.  Will the US take the same blunt, threatening tone with North Korea that we have with Iraq?  Will we threaten to invade?  What makes Iraq and North Korea different?  Isn't our current foriegn policy doctrine to remove threats before they can harm us? It would seem to me the loonies running North Korea, who have also invaded their neighbors and regulary fire shots at South Korean troops and vessels, and who in recent years have test fired a long range ballistic missles over Japan, are at least as serious a threat as Iraq.<br>
<br>
My cynical side says no, we won’t take a hard line with North Korea, because to be blunt, they don’t have oil, and are not in a part of the world where than can threaten our supply.<br>
<br>
I love America.  I love our freedoms.  I love our ideals.  But I’m not so blinded by my patriotism as to think that we somehow have a mandate where we can do no wrong.  Our foreign policy in the Middle East in the 80’s (which created Saddam Hussien’s military might to be a “check” in Iran), Latin American in the 70’s and 80’s, and Southeast Asia in the 60’s are all testament to that fact.  There is a huge difference between patriotism and jingoism, and unfortunately, after Sept. 11th some people have tried to blur those lines to avoid dealing with hard questions.<br>
<br>
My personal opinions on the politics of this mess aside, what scares me more than terrorism is how informed the American public is about the world today.  More than any thing else, what America needs desperately right now are informed citizens making rational judgements based on logic.  Unfortunately, what we have are an awful lot of hurt, angry, or apathetic people who get their news in 15 second sound bites, or from talk radio, that never open a newspaper.  America has survived 200 years of threats from the outside, I think we’ll survive the new threat of terrorism as well.  What concerns me more is what we will end up doing to ourselves in the process.<br>
